Data Description

The dataset used for this project is the GitHub Repositories data from Kaggle that can be accessed here: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/donbarbos/github-repos/data. The dataset has over $215,000$ observations of top GitHub Repositories by star with over $167$ stars. The data was collected using the GitHub search API.

The data set has the following 24 columns:

  • Name : a categorical variable that represents the name of the GitHub repository.
  • Description: a text that is brief textual description that summarizes the purpose or focus of the repository.
  • URL: a text that represents the web address that links to the GitHub repository, which is a unique identifier for the repository.
  • Created At: date-time of class POSIXct that represents the date and time the repository was created on.
  • Updated At: date-time of class POSIXct that represents the date and time of the most recent update to the repo.
  • Homepage: a text that represents the URL to the homepage or landing page associated with the repository, providing additional information or resources.
  • Size: a continous variable that represents the total size of the repositoy in bytes.
  • Stars: a continous variable that represents the number of stars or likes that the repository has received from other GitHub users.
  • Forks: a continous variable that represents the number of times the repository has been forked by other GitHub users.
  • Issues: a continous variable that represents the total number of open issues.
  • Watchers: a continous variable that represents the number of GitHub users who are "watching" or monitoring the repository for updates and changes.
  • Language: a categorical variable that represents the primary programming language of the repository.
  • License: a categorical variable that represents information about the software license using a license identifier.
  • Topic: a list of topics or tags associated with the repository, helping users discover related projects and topics of interest.
  • Has Issues: a categorical variable indicating if the repository has issues or not.
  • Has Projects: a categorical variable indicating whether the repository uses GitHub Projects to manage and organize tasks and work items.
  • Has Downloads: a categorical variable indicating whether the repository offers downloadable files or assets to users.
  • Has Wiki: a categorical variable indicating whether the repository has an associated wiki with additional documentation and information.
  • Has Pages: a categorical variable indicating whether the repository has GitHub Pages enabled, allowing the creation of a website associated with the repository.
  • Has Discussions: a categorical variable indicating whether the repository has GitHub Discussions enabled, allowing community discussions and collaboration.
  • Is Fork: a categorical variable indicating whether the repository is a fork of another repository. In this case, it's false, meaning it is not a fork.
  • Is Archived: a categorical variable indicating whether the repository is archived. Archived repositories are typically read-only and are no longer actively maintained.
  • Is Template: a categorical variable indicating whether the repository is set up as a template.
  • Default Branch: the name of the default branch.

Research Questions

In this project, the response variable is the Stars column, which represents how the number of stars the repository has. The focus of this project is understanding the relationship between Stars and other variables in the dataset. The following questions are of interest:

What is the relationship between the number of starts a Github and the number of issues, forks, and the size of the repository? Is a linear model appropriate for the data? The dataset include all the information needed to answer this question. A linear model can be fitted using the Stars as a response and Forks, Issues, and Size as the covariates, then we can look at the coefficients and their corresponding $p$-values to draw a conclusion about the relationship between them and the response variable.

What combination of variables are significant in predicting the stars a dataset has? To answer this question, we will use forward selection and backward selection to select the variables that are important in the model. Then, we will construct $2$ linear models, one for the variables gotten from forward selection and one for backward selection, and compare their $R^2$ scores.

Data Cleaning

We will drop the following columns because they are not relevant to our questions and they represent text data that will make our model complecated Name, Description, URL, Homepage, Topics and License. Also, instead of of having Created At and Updated At, we will use them to get the age of the repository in days because we expect that an older repository will have more stars in general since it has been on the internet for a long time.

Methods and Plan & Computational Code and Output(individual assignment 2)

Methods and Plan

We will develop two plans for this project, each addressing one of the research questions. The first step of each plan involves splitting the data into training and testing sets. All model training will be conducted on the training set, while the testing set will only be used in the final evaluation stages to ensure unbiased and accurate results.

To investigate the relationship between the number of stars a repository has and its size, number of forks, and number of issues, we will fit a linear regression model. In this model, the number of stars will serve as the response variable, with size, forks, and issues as explanatory variables. We will evaluate the p-values of the coefficients and the $R^2$ value to assess the appropriateness of a linear model. This method assumes constant residual variance (homoscedasticity), independent and normally distributed residuals, and no multicollinearity among predictors. If needed, we may apply log transformations to improve model fit. However, this approach could be limited by the presence of outliers or skewed distributions in the numerical variables, which may reduce accuracy.

For the second research questionidentifying significant predictors of the number of starswe will use variable selection algorithms. Forward selection and backward selection will be applied to find models with the highest adjusted $R^2$, lowest root mean squared error (RMSE), and best $C_p$. The final model will be chosen by comparing the best results from both methods. The assumptions for this approach are the same as those in the first method, with the additional premise that a simpler model with fewer predictors is preferable. However, the process may be limited by the inherent design of the algorithms, which might overlook optimal combinations of predictors where the best combination of variables may not be tested by neither of the two algorithms.

The residuals plot shows a clear funnel shape which indicates heteroscedasticity. We can tackle this by applying a log transformation to Stars. Also, The QQ-plot shows that residuals are not normally distributed.

In[47]:
r_sqr <- function(y_actual, y_predicted) {
    SS_residuals <- sum((y_actual - y_predicted)^2)
    SS_total <- sum((y_actual - mean(y_actual))^2)
    R2 <- 1 - (SS_residuals / SS_total)
    return(R2)
}

The negative $R^2$ indicates that the model's predictions are worse than simply predicting the mean value of the response variable. This poor performance could be caused by the presence of numerous outliers in the data and the highly skewed distribution of the response variable. In conclusion, a linear regression model appears to be an inappropriate choice for modeling the relationship between the number of stars and the repository's size, number of issues, and number of forks.
